# Release-time supply-chain scan (release-reusable.yml `semgrep` step).
# Pinned to current stable to maximise rule coverage at tag-cut time.
# Drift from semgrep-review/requirements.in is intentional (see
# release-reusable.yml comment for the asymmetric-pin policy).
#
# Regenerate the locked requirements.txt on Python 3.14 (matches both the
# `actions/setup-python` version pinned in the consuming workflows and the
# interpreter Dependabot's updater image runs). Run it from INSIDE this
# directory, with these flags — verbatim what Dependabot invokes, so its bump PR
# rewrites only the dependency lines and not the header:
#   cd .github-deps/semgrep-release
#   python3.14 -m venv .tmp/pip-compile-venv
#   .tmp/pip-compile-venv/bin/pip install pip-tools
#   .tmp/pip-compile-venv/bin/pip-compile \
#     --generate-hashes --no-emit-index-url --strip-extras \
#     --output-file=requirements.txt requirements.in
# Unpinned on purpose — see the validate lock's requirements.in for why a `==`
# here breaks Dependabot's pip-compile bump path (#186), and why this directory
# is not under `.github/` (#191). Unlike the review pin, this one is meant to
# track current stable, so Dependabot bumping the lock is exactly the intent.
semgrep
